{{Buddhism-stub}}

The '''Waelz process''' is a method of recovering [[zinc]] and other relatively low boiling point metals from metallurgical waste (typically EAF flue dust) and other recycled materials using a rotary kiln ('''''waelz kiln''''').

The zinc enriched product is referred to as '''''waelz oxide''''', and the reduced zinc by product as '''''waelz slag'''''.

==History and description==
The concept of using a [[rotary kiln]] for the recovery of Zinc by volatization dates to at least 1888.{{sfn|Clay|Schoonraad|1976|p=11}} A process was patented by Edward Dedolph in 1910. Subsequently, the Dedpolph patent was taken up and developed by [[Metallgesellschaft]] (Frankfurt) with [[Chemische Fabrik Griesheim-Elektron]] but without leading to a production scale ready process. In 1923 the [[Krupp Grusonwerk]] independently developed a process (1923), named the ''Waelz process'' (from the German ''Waelzen'', a reference to the motion of the materials in the kiln); the two German firms later collaborated and improved the process marketing under the name ''Waelz-Gemeinschaft'' (German for Waelz association).{{sfn|Harris|1936}}

The process consists of treating zinc containing material, in which zinc can be in the form [[zinc oxide]], [[zinc silicate (disambiguation)|zinc silicate]], [[zinc ferrite]], [[zinc sulphide]] together with a carbon containing reductant/fuel, within a rotary kiln at 1000&nbsp;°C to 1500&nbsp;°C.{{sfn|Clay|Schoonraad|1976|p=11}} The kiln feed material comprising zinc 'waste', fluxes and reductant (coke) is typically pelletized before addition to the kiln.<ref name="z2000"/> The chemical process involves the reduction of zinc compounds to elemental zinc (boiling point 907&nbsp;°C) which volatalises, which oxidises in the vapour phase to zinc oxide. The zinc oxide is collected from the kiln outlet exhaust by filters/electrostatic precipitators/settling chambers etc.{{sfn|Clay|Schoonraad|1976|pp=11, 13}}<ref name="z2000">{{harvnb|Stewart|Daley|Stephens|2000|loc = [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9781118788073.ch29/summary Recovery of Zinc Oxide from secondary raw materials : New developments of the Waelz Process]}}</ref>

Kiln size is typically {{convert|50|by|3.6|m}} long / internal diameter, with a rotation speed of around 1 rpm. The recovered dust (''Waelz oxide'') is enriched in zinc oxide and is a feed product for zinc smelters, the zinc reduced by-product is known as ''Waelz slag''. Sub-optimal features of the process are high energy consumption, and lack of iron recovery (and iron rich slag).<ref name="z2000"/> The process also captures other low boiling metals in the ''waelz oxide'' including lead, cadmium and silver.{{sfn|Antrekowitsch|Steinlechner|Unger|Rösler|2014|p=118}} Halogen compounds are also present in the product oxide.{{sfn|Antrekowitsch|Steinlechner|Unger|Rösler|2014|p=119}}

Increased use of [[galvanised]] steel has resulted in increased levels of zinc in steel scrap which in turn leads to higher levels of zinc in [[electric arc furnace]] flue dusts - as of 2000 the waelz process is considered to be a "[[best available technology]]" for flue dust zinc recovery, and the process is used at industrial scale worldwide.{{sfn|Stewart|Daley|Stephens|2000|loc = [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9781118788073.ch29/summary Recovery of Zinc Oxide from secondary raw materials : New developments of the Waelz Process]}}

As of 2014 the Waelz process is the preferred or most widely used process for zinc recovery of zinc from [[electric arc furnace]] dust (90%).{{sfn|Antrekowitsch|Steinlechner|Unger|Rösler|2014|pp=117-118, 119}}

Alternative production and experimental scale zinc recovery processes include the rotary hearth treatment of pelletised zinc containing dust ([[Kimitsu Steel Works|Kimitsu works]], Nippon Steel);<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.nssmc.com/en/tech/report/nsc/pdf/8607.pdf| title = Dust Recycling Technology by the Rotary Hearth Furnace| first = Hiroshi|last  =Oda| first2 = Tetsuharu| last2 = Ibaraki| first3= Masaharu| last3 = Takahashi| work = Nippon Steel Technical Report| number = 86| date = July 2002}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url= http://mmmmconferences.com/01JyunpeiKikuta_29Sept2012.pdf | title = Dust Recycling System by the Rotary Hearth Furnace| first = Hiroshi|last  =Oda| first2 = Tetsuharu| last2 = Ibaraki| first3= Youichi| last3 = Abe | work = Nippon Steel Technical Report| number = 94| date = July 2006}}</ref> the SDHL (Saage, Dittrich, Hasche, Langbein) process, an efficiency modification of the Waelz process;<ref name="z2000"/> the "DK process" a modified blast furnace process producing pig iron and zinc (oxide) dust from blast furnace dusts, sludges and other wastes;<ref>{{citation| url = http://www.dk-duisburg.de/en/unternehmen/img/artikel_stahleisen2006.pdf| title = Solutions for dusts and sludges from the BOF process| first = Carsten|last = Hillmann| first2= Karl-Josef| last2 = Sassen| journal = Stahl und Eisin| volume = 126| year = 2006| number = 11}}</ref> and the PRIMUS process (multi-stage zinc volatilisation furnace).<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = J. L. | first1 =  Roth | last2 = R. | first2 =  Frieden|first3= T. |last3=Hansmann|first4= J. |last4= Monai|first5=M. |last5=Solvi | date  = Nov 2001  | title = PRIMUS, a new process for recycling by-products and producing virgin iron | journal = Revue de Métallurgie | volume = 98 | issue = 11 | pages = 987–996 | publisher =  | jstor =  | doi = 10.1051/metal:2001140 | url =  | format = |ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url = http://www.innovation.public.lu/en/success-stories/2003/primus-paul-wurth/index.html|title  = The PRIMUS process by Paul Wurth: cutting-edge technology for recycling iron and steel by-products by direct reduction | date = 3 Aug 2003| work = www.innovation.public.lu}}</ref>

